defaultSurvey Resultsdefault&#xa0;
defaultThe survey focused on NIIRTA members’ ability to access finance, credit card and overdraft services, the bank branch closure programme and overall customer satisfaction with their 
defaultbanks.
default&#xa0;
defaultThis is the first ever survey of the views on banking services from independent retailers across Northern Ireland and shows that a majority of those surveyed are satisfied with the services they receive from local banks
default.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default65% of those who have applied for finance within the last three years were successful in accessing it, which suggests an improving trend given the
default difficult trading conditions of
default the last year.
default&#xa0;
defaultHowever banks still have some way to go in this area as 35% w
defaultere turned down for finance.
default 
defaultWe hope that when we repeat this survey next year there will be great improvement shown in this area.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default64% of those surveyed have an overdraft with a third of them unhappy as their bank had unilaterally change
defaultd the conditions of the overdraft re
defaultsulting in a negative impact on 
defaulttheir business.
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;
default62% of those surveyed have a company credit card with only 3% claiming that their bank had altered the contract to the detriment of their business.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultGiven the recent closure of bank branches, we were keen to see how this had impacted on footfall and spending patterns.
default 
defaultWhile 76% said there has been no impact, 24% said they have been affected.
default 
defaultRural members especially expressed concern a
defaultt the greater distances they now had to travel to their local banks to lodge money.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default42% rate the service from their bank as good or excellent, 38% average and 20% below average or poor. The banking sector overall will be happy with 
defaultthis figure and it demonstrates that they have responded to pressure from our members and Government to improve.
